`agents/` is the model-invocation boundary for the summarization pipeline — it turns a runner-assembled prompt into a completion string, isolating the CLI from any specifics of which model API is called.

Currently a single adapter, summarizer-claude.py, implements the stdin/stdout contract: read `{"system", "user", "model"}` as JSON from stdin, call one external API once, write the raw completion to stdout, errors/exit codes to stderr. Any future sibling adapter (e.g. for a different provider) must honor this same contract exactly — the Rust CLI selects an adapter and expects this I/O shape regardless of which one runs. Prompt content and structure are owned upstream in `prompts/`; adapters must not add instructions of their own, only transport.

Because the summarizer prompt is reused verbatim across every leaf/rollup call in a task, adapters should exploit provider-side prompt caching where available rather than resending the same tokens per call — this is a cost invariant that would carry over to any new adapter, not just the Claude one.

